AB Integrating two disparate functions in organizations-marketing and
   information services (IS)-has become a critical business concern due to
   the increasing use of information technology (IT) to find and open new
   markets, deliver improved services to customers, and streamline internal
   marketing processes. This study appears to be the first to empirically
   examine the dynamics of bringing these distinct groups of specialists
   together. We investigate potential antecedents, consequences, and
   contingencies of IS-marketing integration, drawing on theories of
   complementarity and competence. Through a survey of IS and marketing
