   growth, (4) identifies the two major, radically different, theories of
   economic growth: neoclassical, static-equilibrium growth theory and
   dynamic competition growth theory, (5) shows how the two theories make
   four radically different, testable predictions, and (6) reviews the
   empirical evidence concerning the four predictions. The article
   concludes that the equity and needs/wants challenges of sustainable
   development and the cause of sustainable development more generally can
   be addressed by poor nations pursuing economic growth, which in turn
